    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="26"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d26">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Presidents Naval Aide</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BFDW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Brown</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Presidents Military Aide and
                        Secretary</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WEM1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Watson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d26fn1">The original of this message, all of it
                        in <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>’s handwriting, contained
                        the signature “<persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>” and the
                        following concluding sentence: “Do not tell him this is sent by the
                        President.” These words were stricken out, and the signature “<persName
                            corresp="#p_BW1">Wilson Brown</persName>” was added by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>. The copy of the message as
                        received in the White House bears the notation: “acted on by Gen <persName
                            corresp="#p_WEM1">Watson</persName> A M 25th. <persName
                            corresp="#p_BRW2">R[obert] W B[ogue]</persName>”.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quebec</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-25">August 25,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>To General <persName corresp="#p_WEM1">Watson</persName>.</p>
                <p>You will please send for the Soviet Chargé d’Affaires and give him the following
                    in your capacity as Secretary to the President, which he may feel at liberty to
                    transmit to Marshal <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“The Marshal’s message to the President and the Prime Minister<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d26fn2">This is the message of August 22, 1943, printed in <hi
                                rend="italic">
                                <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s Correspondence</hi>,
                            vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 84. According to <persName
                                corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName> (p. 94), <persName
                                corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> was “very much offended at
                            the tone of this message”, which concerned the negotiations for the
                            armistice with Italy.</note> has been transmitted to the President, who
                        has left the conference in Quebec and because of absence, will not be
                        available until early next week.</p>
                    <p>“Any reply by the Marshal to the telegram from the President and the Prime
                        Minister to the Marshal relating to a joint meeting will of course be
                        transmitted to them.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson Brown</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
